    base:desc "The framework defines a five‑stage lifecycle for a building Digital Twin: (1) Device modelling in BIM – Building Control Engineers create custom Revit families and property sets for sensors, actuators and controllers, assign a unique Instance General UUID and set the appropriate IFC type (e.g., IFCLIGHTFIXTURETYPE). (2) Model checking – an IFC‑based model checker validates that all required metadata is present before the model is uploaded. (3) Semantic model extraction (F2) – model‑to‑model transformations generate a structured, domain‑specific representation from the enriched BIM/IFC file. (4) Automated one‑click deployment (F3) – the extracted model drives a model‑to‑text transformation that produces, configures and launches the DT runtime artifacts with minimal manual effort. (5) Runtime operation – live bidirectional data exchange (F4) via Eclipse Hono and Ditto keeps the physical building and its digital counterpart synchronised; interactive 3D visualisation (F5) in UE5 enables immersive monitoring; modular service integration (F6) and runtime configuration management (F7) allow new analytics or control services to be added or re‑configured without redeploying the whole twin. Governance is split across three roles: Building Control Engineer (modeling and deployment), Facility Manager (monitoring and control) and DT Engineer (service extension)."
